statement.p:
Let \(\mathcal{L}=[L; \lor, \land ]\) be a lattice under \(\leq\).  \(\mathcal{L}\) is called a distributive lattice if and only if the distributive laws hold; that is, for all \(a, b, c \in  L\) we have

\begin{array}{c}
a \lor  (b \land  c) = (a \lor  b) \land  (a \lor  c)\\
and \\
a \land  (b \lor  c) = (a \land  b) \lor  (a \land  c)\\
\end{array}
